01:10:13,398 --> 01:10:14,239
What is the salary?

961
01:10:14,799 --> 01:10:16,420
And the gentleman who was the principal there,

962
01:10:16,870 --> 01:10:19,291
Where is he up at the high school, and what is that salary?

963
01:10:19,991 --> 01:10:20,291
You got it?

964
01:10:22,452 --> 01:10:24,432
Roll call has been requested by Councilor Penta.

965
01:10:30,354 --> 01:10:31,174
Councilor Dela Russo?

966
01:10:31,194 --> 01:10:33,595
No.

967
01:10:33,635 --> 01:10:34,175
Councilor Knight?

968
01:10:34,295 --> 01:10:34,435
No.

969
01:10:35,396 --> 01:10:36,116
Councilor McKernan?

970
01:10:36,376 --> 01:10:36,576
Yes.

971
01:10:38,336 --> 01:10:38,957
Councilor Mox?

972
01:10:39,517 --> 01:10:39,737
Yes.

973
01:10:40,717 --> 01:10:41,337
Councilor Penta?

974
01:10:41,397 --> 01:10:41,697
Yes.

975
01:10:42,738 --> 01:10:43,318
President Camuso?

976
01:10:43,658 --> 01:10:47,781
Yes, by a vote of four in the affirmative, five in the affirmative, two in the negative, the motion passes.

977
01:10:49,182 --> 01:10:52,124
Item 14-725, offered by Councilor Penta.

978
01:10:54,185 --> 01:11:02,131
Be it resolved, the city prepare a forward paying program starting with, in a clerical error here, this is to read, according to Councilor Penta, 500,000 rather than 5,000.

979
01:11:02,211 --> 01:11:02,771
No, 500 is written.

980
01:11:02,791 --> 01:11:03,852
500 rather than 50.

981
01:11:10,081 --> 01:11:10,741
Is that correct, Councilor?

982
01:11:10,841 --> 01:11:11,181
It should be $500,000.

983
01:11:11,441 --> 01:11:12,021
Yes.

984
01:11:12,521 --> 01:11:12,802
OK.

985
01:11:12,962 --> 01:11:13,282
A year.

986
01:11:13,302 --> 01:11:14,302
I'm going to start again.

987
01:11:15,202 --> 01:11:25,184
Be it resolved the city prepare a forward paying program starting with a $500,000 a year payment from the free cash account to begin offsetting the city's unfunded pension liability.

988
01:11:25,224 --> 01:11:25,844
Councilor Penta.

989
01:11:26,044 --> 01:11:33,026
Mr. President, we've had this discussion numerous times in the past as it relates to the unfunded liability that the city has been involved in.

990
01:11:34,046 --> 01:11:38,507
And nothing, there's absolutely been no discussion by the city.

991
01:11:38,587 --> 01:11:39,927
There's been nothing coming forward.

992
01:11:40,570 --> 01:11:47,774
It's bad enough we've had our discussion relative to the water and sewer account sitting on $8.5 million, and ratepayers are getting no relief.

993
01:11:48,775 --> 01:11:58,980
But we have over $6.5 million in our free cash account, and it would be a good beginning if we started with a $500,000 a year and just moved itself forward.

994
01:11:59,280 --> 01:12:08,425
You know, if this council wants to leave itself with some type of legacy as it relates to its fiscal responsibility, this would be one of them.

995
01:12:09,389 --> 01:12:12,291
I don't think we should be given anything by the way of the administration.

996
01:12:12,731 --> 01:12:15,872
Well, we're going to come in here and we're going to bond this to get ourselves going.

997
01:12:16,693 --> 01:12:17,573
It doesn't go that way.

998
01:12:18,533 --> 01:12:28,178
This city, the people in this city have been taxed to death between the state and the feds and the city and everything that's going on.

999
01:12:28,598 --> 01:12:37,562
But if we're sitting on this kind of money and we know we have this debt to pay, we should be upfront about it and start doing it and not leave this for any future city councils.

1000
01:12:38,009 --> 01:12:40,930
or any future administration to come in as being a headache.

1001
01:12:42,670 --> 01:12:47,871
We get on an annual basis a federal reimbursement from Part D. Last year, we got $335,000.

1002
01:12:47,911 --> 01:12:50,272
We got $335,000 from Part D, which is the Medicare Part D reimbursement.

1003
01:12:50,292 --> 01:12:52,972
We were also identified in the state retirees annual review as having an 11.3%

1004
01:13:09,724 --> 01:13:13,906
11.31% return for the last five years on our investments.

1005
01:13:14,907 --> 01:13:36,580
But if you look at Malden and if you go to other cities and towns which have a higher rate of return, again, I think it's something that this council has asked for before to maybe to sit down with our retirement board and to go over the type of investments that they have and see where maybe we can streamline and make more and understand why and how other cities and towns

1006
01:13:37,018 --> 01:13:37,598
can do better.

1007
01:13:38,479 --> 01:13:44,702
It's not that we're doing that bad, but if somebody can do better, then we should be able to have that ability to look forward as well as that.

1008
01:13:45,222 --> 01:13:48,163
But I think this is a serious bone of contention.

1009
01:13:48,843 --> 01:13:50,004
I think this is something.

1010
01:13:50,444 --> 01:13:52,965
This isn't something that maybe we can or can't do.

1011
01:13:53,005 --> 01:13:54,826
This is something we have to do.

1012
01:13:55,206 --> 01:14:00,129
This city is obligated to pay its unfunded liability as it relates to its pensions.

1013
01:14:00,929 --> 01:14:02,450
It's well into the millions of dollars.

1014
01:14:02,470 --> 01:14:03,630
This isn't the hundreds of thousands.

1015
01:14:03,930 --> 01:14:05,271
It's well into the millions of dollars.

1016
01:14:05,958 --> 01:14:28,197
And I think if we start nibbling away at it with $500,000 in the first year, setting the example, and each and every year going forward, as we're paying down the at-present cost on an annual basis, it'll greatly reduce the trauma, the fiscal trauma, because that's what it's going to be when the city has to financially realize they've got to pay for this thing.

1017
01:14:28,817 --> 01:14:30,239
I believe it's 2029 is the deadline, 2030 is the deadline.

1018
01:14:34,545 --> 01:14:36,506
And we're no closer to having this thing resolved.

1019
01:14:37,086 --> 01:14:41,168
And each and every year, as the years go on, this keeps getting itself compounded.

1020
01:14:41,708 --> 01:14:51,532
So, with that being said, Mr. President, I spoke to Ann Baker about this, a city auditor, and she believes it's a good — it's a good move forward.

1021
01:14:52,232 --> 01:14:56,054
At least we're addressing the subject matter, and that's what we need to do.

1022
01:14:56,174 --> 01:15:01,296
And let me just, once again, say we shouldn't be leaving this type of a debt for any future council.

1023
01:15:01,996 --> 01:15:04,097
And if the administration doesn't want to address it,

1024
01:15:04,607 --> 01:15:05,167
Shame on them.

1025
01:15:05,528 --> 01:15:10,630
This is taking a very proactive approach going forward and recognizing this debt has to get paid.

1026
01:15:11,151 --> 01:15:22,877
And to get it paid, knowing that we're flush in our free cash account right now, and it's been an accumulation through the years to get to $6.5 million, I don't think this is going to hurt the city's bank at all.

1027
01:15:22,897 --> 01:15:26,999
And at the same time, we're addressing the subject matter that needs to be addressed.

1028
01:15:27,439 --> 01:15:34,003
So that being said, Mr. President, I'd like to move that by a roll call vote to our city auditor and our finance department.

1029
01:15:35,688 --> 01:15:41,532
and get the city on some kind of a system here that addresses this financial liability that it needs to address.

1030
01:15:41,552 --> 01:15:43,354
Point of information.

1031
01:15:43,374 --> 01:15:44,314
Point of information.

1032
01:15:44,394 --> 01:15:46,096
Councillor DelaRusso, then Councillor Knight.

1033
01:15:47,036 --> 01:15:49,978
If I could just ask, what is the amount of money owed?

1034
01:15:51,640 --> 01:15:54,202
I believe it's in excess of $20 million the city owes.

1035
01:15:55,082 --> 01:15:55,422
Thank you.

1036
01:15:56,583 --> 01:15:57,204
Councillor Knight.

1037
01:15:57,264 --> 01:15:58,545
It's unfunded pension liability.

1038
01:15:59,005 --> 01:16:00,326
Thank you very much, Mr. President.

1039
01:16:00,846 --> 01:16:02,968
And thank you, Councillor Pinto, for bringing this issue up.

1040
01:16:04,023 --> 01:16:05,324
I certainly agree with some of your points.

1041
01:16:05,364 --> 01:16:07,505
However, I urge my colleagues to move with caution.

1042
01:16:08,265 --> 01:16:29,194
Recently, I believe this fiscal year, GASB, which is the Government Accounting Standards Bureau, has come out with a number of papers which will change the way that we're allowed to forecast and we're allowed to report our liabilities on our balance sheets, which means that if we're reporting liabilities that are less than what we have, our balance sheets are going to be off and we're actually going to go and owe more money.

1043
01:16:29,760 --> 01:16:44,429
So if we owe more money on our liabilities that aren't showing up on our balance sheets now but will be later on, and we're spending money of our free cash to offset this, we might have a perilous effect on our bond rating, Mr. President, because we're going to be taking money out of our reserves to pay for this unfunded liability.

1044
01:16:44,709 --> 01:16:49,672
With these new reforms that are coming in place and these new reporting requirements, I think that we need to move with caution.

1045
01:16:49,692 --> 01:16:58,797
I think we need to get a report back from the Retirement Board as to what steps they've taken to address the generally accepted accounting principles that have been adopted by the federal government and passed down to the state.

1046
01:16:59,575 --> 01:17:07,965
I think that it's important to understand that the unfunded liability is really a mismatch between the estimated returns that we have on our long-term investments and the estimated assets that we have.

1047
01:17:08,065 --> 01:17:12,810
So in looking at what's happened, the GASB group has

1048
01:17:14,897 --> 01:17:17,058
really taking a look at the way that we forecast.

1049
01:17:17,358 --> 01:17:29,325
And municipalities usually forecast at a rate upwards of 8 percent, while private sector pension plans usually forecast at around a rate of 4 percent, which is a little bit more in line with what the actual returns on investments are.

1050
01:17:29,786 --> 01:17:38,571
Now, as I've done further research, I've seen that the 25 largest pension systems for municipalities are returning at about 7.5 percent or 7.25 percent.

1051
01:17:38,911 --> 01:17:40,912
So there's certainly some concern here, Mr. President.

1052
01:17:41,418 --> 01:17:43,279
I think that we need to be on strong financial footing.

1053
01:17:43,319 --> 01:17:55,605
We need to make sure that we keep money in the bank, and we need to be sure that we don't have a perilous effect on our bond rating before we move forward and start, you know, issuing annual checks for $500,000 a year to offset this pension liability.

1054
01:17:55,865 --> 01:17:56,645
It might not be enough.

1055
01:17:56,685 --> 01:17:57,466
It might be too much.

1056
01:17:57,846 --> 01:18:04,889
There might not be a break-even there, and our bond rate is going to start to drop, and our pension liability is going to go up because of the new reporting requirements, Mr. President.

1057
01:18:04,909 --> 01:18:07,070
So I urge my colleagues to proceed with caution.

1058
01:18:07,511 --> 01:18:10,512
For those reasons and the uncertainty, I'm going to be voting against this resolution.

1059
01:18:12,415 --> 01:18:13,435
Councilor DelaRusso.

1060
01:18:16,036 --> 01:18:18,356
I'm sorry, Vice President Caravaglia and then Councilor DelaRusso.

1061
01:18:18,516 --> 01:18:19,616
Thank you, Mr. President.

1062
01:18:19,636 --> 01:18:20,617
I agree with Councilor Penter.

1063
01:18:21,357 --> 01:18:23,137
We do need to stop paying this off.

1064
01:18:23,157 --> 01:18:25,998
This has been one of my bones of contention during every budget.

1065
01:18:26,818 --> 01:18:36,760
But before I vote for this, I'd like to sit down with the retirement board and Baker and our budget director to see exactly where we stand and what this $500,000 does to us.

1066
01:18:39,680 --> 01:18:42,082
if we're using the correct formula going forward.

1067
01:18:43,102 --> 01:18:57,833
So I'd rather have a committee meeting on the whole before I vote on this Mr. Penta, just to see where we stand before we allocate any further funding.

1068
01:18:57,973 --> 01:19:04,798
Though I do agree, the amount that's owed is quite large, and if I'm not mistaken,

1069
01:19:06,232 --> 01:19:13,274
I think Ian Baker said like 2032 or 36 was the projected date that they have for it to be funded.

1070
01:19:13,294 --> 01:19:18,615
But I'd like to see where we stand with all these people before we make a commitment.

1071
01:19:19,876 --> 01:19:20,736
Councilor DelaRusso.

1072
01:19:21,196 --> 01:19:24,537
Mr. President, I want to thank Councilor Penta for bringing this up.

1073
01:19:25,097 --> 01:19:34,480
And I'm supportive of this, but I think perhaps before we do vote on this and set a dollar amount to it,

1074
01:19:35,676 --> 01:19:55,544
the wise course of action given the information that Councilor Nigel shared with us and also Councilor Caraviello's concerns would be that we meet, perhaps the Finance and Budgeting Committee meet with all those persons who were mentioned by Councilor Caraviello to examine the matter.

1075
01:19:55,744 --> 01:20:05,388
But it is a critically serious issue and it needs to be addressed and dragging our feet on it is not the right thing to do.

1076
01:20:05,922 --> 01:20:09,943
So you're perfectly right there, Councilor Penta, that this should be moved on.

1077
01:20:10,444 --> 01:20:20,587
I think the way to do it would be to develop a plan with those pertinent persons and start to move on it.

1078
01:20:21,467 --> 01:20:24,008
And we can do it within this budget cycle.

1079
01:20:25,109 --> 01:20:25,489
Thank you.

1080
01:20:26,089 --> 01:20:26,969
Councilor Lungo-Kern.

1081
01:20:28,370 --> 01:20:29,970
Thank you, President Camuso.

1082
01:20:29,990 --> 01:20:34,872
I was going to agree with Councilor Caravaglio that we sit in subcommittee with Anne Baker.

1083
01:20:35,445 --> 01:20:39,447
The same exact people, Ian Baker, budget director, and the retirement board.

1084
01:20:39,467 --> 01:20:42,249
I would like to learn a little bit more.

1085
01:20:42,489 --> 01:20:46,171
I'm not ready to make a vote on it tonight, but I agree with my colleagues.

1086
01:20:46,611 --> 01:20:48,152
And I thank Councilor Penta for bringing this up.

1087
01:20:48,652 --> 01:20:49,373
Councilor Penta.

1088
01:20:49,393 --> 01:21:01,219
Mr. President, as I said before, I'm going to disagree with my colleague, Councilor Knight, because the facts that he has are not representative of the cost

1089
01:21:03,148 --> 01:21:04,709
that's presently out there.

1090
01:21:04,929 --> 01:21:10,131
The city of Medford, for example, on a return for its money last year, received 11.96%.

1091
01:21:10,171 --> 01:21:12,511
But you go to Northbridge, they had 15.29%.

1092
01:21:12,551 --> 01:21:12,872
Norwood, 15.84%.

1093
01:21:12,912 --> 01:21:13,232
Peabody had 15.34%.

1094
01:21:13,272 --> 01:21:13,732
Pittsfield had 14.91%.

1095
01:21:13,772 --> 01:21:14,312
Plymouth had 19.66%.

1096
01:21:14,352 --> 01:21:16,113
And then you can go down to these other cities and towns.

1097
01:21:16,133 --> 01:21:16,613
Weymouth had 18.2%.

1098
01:21:32,142 --> 01:21:33,363
Winchester had 12 point.

1099
01:21:34,264 --> 01:21:35,564
Winthrop had 14 percent.

1100
01:21:35,664 --> 01:21:37,005
Woburn had 18 percent.

1101
01:21:37,986 --> 01:21:50,895
And we can go down, and the question then becomes if our investments aren't meeting or keeping up with those folks, those folks who apparently are doing better than the city of Medford, why?

1102
01:21:51,215 --> 01:21:55,658
And maybe we should be looking at taking a lesson from how they do their investments.

1103
01:21:55,698 --> 01:21:56,378
That's number one.

1104
01:21:56,438 --> 01:21:59,020
Number two, this is a debt obligation that we owe.

1105
01:21:59,299 --> 01:22:17,048
And if this city is going to keep worrying about its bond rating, its bond rating has got nothing to do with paying off a debt because you show me the alternative other than taking it out of the money that you already have, other than going out to bond to want to pay for this thing, which would be the most ridiculous way to go.

1106
01:22:17,989 --> 01:22:23,732
This city administration is paralyzing, is taking money away from Medford taxpayers

1107
01:22:24,142 --> 01:22:28,785
that either could be used for paying debts such as this or municipal improvements.

1108
01:22:29,245 --> 01:22:31,407
This is just two particular areas.

1109
01:22:31,947 --> 01:22:37,110
And if you're going to keep being worried about a bond, well, what's the next big thing to get bonded around here?

1110
01:22:37,410 --> 01:22:38,171
The police station?

1111
01:22:38,771 --> 01:22:41,073
Well, then let's do it if that's what we're waiting for.

1112
01:22:41,453 --> 01:22:44,075
But according to the mayor, that's a seven-year-old process.

1113
01:22:44,795 --> 01:22:46,816
This is something that's alive and well.

1114
01:22:47,077 --> 01:22:48,858
It's in front of your faces right now.

1115
01:22:49,278 --> 01:22:58,947
This is a debt obligation that's owed because the city, for which has been this administration for 26 years, has never put a dime into paying or paying down on this debt obligation.

1116
01:22:59,327 --> 01:23:00,428
And now it's in front of us.

1117
01:23:00,809 --> 01:23:01,609
And it's real.

1118
01:23:01,930 --> 01:23:03,151
And it has to be addressed.

1119
01:23:03,551 --> 01:23:05,233
I'm not worried about a bond rating.

1120
01:23:05,493 --> 01:23:13,060
I'm more concerned about if we have money sitting in the bank that can start to help to pay this debt down, then that's what we need to do.

1121
01:23:14,106 --> 01:23:22,830
For God's sakes, you get $8.5 million in a water and sewer account, and the city administration is afraid either to lower the rates or have a program set.

1122
01:23:23,210 --> 01:23:25,171
Those are the only two things you can do with a surplus.

1123
01:23:25,831 --> 01:23:30,813
And he's being allowed to just get away with doing nothing and letting the money accumulate.

1124
01:23:31,373 --> 01:23:33,474
And here you are, $6.5 million in free cash.

1125
01:23:34,334 --> 01:23:40,237
But you also have a debt obligation that exists each and every year and continues to grow.

1126
01:23:41,160 --> 01:23:42,641
This is not going to go away.

1127
01:23:42,661 --> 01:23:44,781
This isn't a political issue.

1128
01:23:45,062 --> 01:23:50,504
This is a real, live, physical debt obligation that this city owes.

1129
01:23:51,444 --> 01:23:54,745
And with that being said, $500,000 is a drop in the bucket.

1130
01:23:55,025 --> 01:23:55,826
It's a beginning.

1131
01:23:56,426 --> 01:24:00,247
It's a beginning to understand that we are going to address this problem.

1132
01:24:00,768 --> 01:24:04,189
And if we're fortunate enough to keep going and having free cash,

1133
01:24:04,815 --> 01:24:07,476
then maybe that's the best way to just keep going.

1134
01:24:07,816 --> 01:24:17,221
Because I don't know any other way other than going out and, again, banging the taxpayer overhead by way of a bond or some other financial encumbrance that they're going to have to pay for this.

1135
01:24:17,481 --> 01:24:18,662
And they shouldn't have to pay for it.

1136
01:24:19,322 --> 01:24:29,006
But when other cities and towns, other cities and towns can generate that kind of money by a rate of interest return for their last year, and we did 11 percent.

1137
01:24:29,106 --> 01:24:30,707
We're somewhere in the middle or thereabouts.

1138
01:24:31,127 --> 01:24:34,489
But there are other cities and towns well ahead of us with their interest returns.

1139
01:24:34,883 --> 01:24:39,824
Then I think we need to have a — sit down with the Retirement Board and Baker and all our financial people.

1140
01:24:40,084 --> 01:24:40,944
But that's not the point.

1141
01:24:41,344 --> 01:24:42,925
This issue has got to be addressed.

1142
01:24:43,425 --> 01:24:49,946
And the best way to address it, knowing right now that we're flushing at least one particular account, then let's get to it and let's start on it.

1143
01:24:50,206 --> 01:25:01,789
And let's not worry about, oh, my God, we might go from a triple-A to a double-A bond rating because we used money that the taxpayers have that are generally theirs that's not being used for anything else.

1144
01:25:02,049 --> 01:25:04,169
We're waiting for this administration to decide

1145
01:25:04,536 --> 01:25:06,878
the next thing he wants to do to use the money on.

1146
01:25:07,679 --> 01:25:16,486
And then maybe when he leaves next year or two years or whenever he decides to go or gets beaten out of office, that administration is going to have to deal with it.

1147
01:25:17,086 --> 01:25:19,228
That city council is going to have to deal with it.

1148
01:25:19,628 --> 01:25:22,351
And then it will affect every single thing that a budget has.

1149
01:25:22,651 --> 01:25:33,840
But if there's a commitment that's built in now, and it represents the fact that we're addressing this debt that wasn't started by this council or councils before, it's been sitting there for years,

1150
01:25:34,239 --> 01:25:38,222
because no city administration wanted to deal with it, now's the time to do it.

1151
01:25:38,642 --> 01:25:41,645
All you have to do is pony up, however you want to do it.

1152
01:25:41,705 --> 01:25:42,465
Do you want to have a meeting?

1153
01:25:42,646 --> 01:25:43,526
I've got no problem with it.

1154
01:25:44,087 --> 01:25:52,954
But as Councilor De La Rosa, you alluded to it, it should be addressed this term, and the first payment should begin during this legislative session that we're serving in.

1155
01:25:54,215 --> 01:25:55,235
Vice President Caravaglio.

1156
01:25:55,536 --> 01:25:56,176
Thank you, Mr. President.

1157
01:25:56,456 --> 01:26:03,822
You know, not only do we have this debt going to people that have already retired, but I want to see where we're going forward

1158
01:26:04,186 --> 01:26:07,887
for these younger people that are coming down the line.

1159
01:26:07,927 --> 01:26:12,149
I mean, when was the last time this formula was re-evaluated?

1160
01:26:13,169 --> 01:26:16,030
Has it been increased, decreased over the years?

1161
01:26:16,090 --> 01:26:16,890
That's what I want to see.

1162
01:26:17,690 --> 01:26:28,994
Going forward, I mean, what's in the past is done, but there's a lot of young people that are working in the city that depend on this pension for when they retire in the next 20, 25, or 30 years.

1163
01:26:29,514 --> 01:26:31,115
That's the part where I'm concerned,

1164
01:26:32,346 --> 01:26:34,507
Are we using the correct formula going forward?

1165
01:26:35,808 --> 01:26:36,369
Councillor Knight.

1166
01:26:38,130 --> 01:26:39,351
Thank you, Councillor Caviello.

1167
01:26:39,471 --> 01:26:40,331
That's what I was getting at.

1168
01:26:40,351 --> 01:26:53,040
You know, with GASB making these changes to the actual accounting and reporting principles that are in place and the federal government adopting them as generally accepted accounting principles, the city of Medford is going to have to take a look at the way that we are doing things.

1169
01:26:53,740 --> 01:26:55,161
I'm not saying that this is a bad idea.

1170
01:26:55,181 --> 01:26:56,462
I didn't say that at all.

1171
01:26:57,153 --> 01:27:04,456
What I'm saying is I think we need to tread lightly and we need to use caution because we don't want to make a decision that's going to have a long-term dramatic effect on our financial viability.

1172
01:27:04,836 --> 01:27:11,279
Now, I understand what Councilor Pinto is coming from, saying, well, we're never going to have financial viability if we have this unfunded debt and this unfunded liability.

1173
01:27:11,719 --> 01:27:16,041
However, if we're looking at how we're going to pay it off and we have the free cash sitting in the bank collecting 1%,

1174
01:27:17,207 --> 01:27:26,095
And we can take that money out and bond it for 2 or 3 or 4 percent because we have a AAA bond rating and then use that to spend down a pension liability that's going to get us a return to 15 percent, like he says.

1175
01:27:26,135 --> 01:27:27,035
I don't see how we're losing money.

1176
01:27:27,636 --> 01:27:29,618
But that's a question for another day, Mr. President.

1177
01:27:29,638 --> 01:27:42,448
I'll certainly support the paper to go to committee to ask these questions that we have to get better informed and to properly vet the issue before we make a demand or make a — ask the question for the mayor to expend $500,000 annually to fully fund the pension system.

1178
01:27:42,869 --> 01:27:44,690
I know that we've gotten a report back from Ann Baker.

1179
01:27:44,710 --> 01:27:45,511
I believe it was in April.

1180
01:27:45,968 --> 01:27:47,989
relative to the plan that they currently have in place.

1181
01:27:48,049 --> 01:27:56,911
However, I don't have any understanding or any commitment or any knowledge that the city's actually looking at these new accounting principles and these new accounting standards that have been put in place.

1182
01:27:57,271 --> 01:27:59,171
That's why I asked my colleagues to tread lightly.

1183
01:27:59,491 --> 01:28:06,333
That's why I think this issue needs to be vetted a little bit further before we can ask this question and make this recommendation, Mr. President.

1184
01:28:07,333 --> 01:28:07,653
Thank you.

1185
01:28:07,753 --> 01:28:08,314
Councilor Fenton.

1186
01:28:08,334 --> 01:28:11,194
Mr. President, to bond 2 percent, maybe you misspoke.

1187
01:28:11,514 --> 01:28:13,915
You said maybe we should just go out and bond for 2 percent.

1188
01:28:14,248 --> 01:28:16,050
and that money will generate some money.

1189
01:28:16,790 --> 01:28:18,812
Why would you be going out to bond 2% to pay?

1190
01:28:19,312 --> 01:28:21,694
When you go out to bond, you're bonding for something.

1191
01:28:23,316 --> 01:28:24,036
I think you misspoke.

1192
01:28:24,257 --> 01:28:25,217
I don't understand what you said.

1193
01:28:25,277 --> 01:28:26,699
You said you bond for 2%?

1194
01:28:26,739 --> 01:28:29,641
You're saying we're getting returns of 15%, 20%, right?

1195
01:28:30,041 --> 01:28:31,803
Other communities are getting returns of 15% or 20%, right?

1196
01:28:31,823 --> 01:28:33,204
Those are, yeah.

1197
01:28:33,224 --> 01:28:38,529
So if we bond the money for 3% and we invest that money and we're getting returns of 15%, I don't see how we're losing.

1198
01:28:40,030 --> 01:28:42,332
That's not the investment that's going.

1199
01:28:43,365 --> 01:28:52,350
If you look at how the Retirement Board invests its money, and if you read the State Investment Board Retirement Program, it's to pay for the investments that you have right now.

1200
01:28:52,710 --> 01:28:54,531
We're talking about the unfunded liability.

1201
01:28:54,751 --> 01:28:58,033
It doesn't make any difference what the Feds or Gatsby or anybody else says.

1202
01:28:58,273 --> 01:29:01,855
You're going to have to—and whatever the new accounting practices might be, they still

1203
01:29:02,527 --> 01:29:04,548
can't get you away from the fact that you owe this money.

1204
01:29:05,028 --> 01:29:10,091
And however you owe this money, if this money is put aside in a special account to offset it, so be it.

1205
01:29:10,432 --> 01:29:12,353
We're not putting up $6 or $7 million.

1206
01:29:12,573 --> 01:29:14,634
We're starting at a $500,000 beginning here.

1207
01:29:14,654 --> 01:29:15,915
But what I'm saying is, why not?

1208
01:29:15,955 --> 01:29:21,478
Why aren't we putting up $6 or $7 million if that's going to address the problem and address the need and address it now, in the real time, right now?

1209
01:29:21,538 --> 01:29:22,299
Why aren't we doing that?

1210
01:29:22,599 --> 01:29:24,420
Well, then if that's the case, then maybe we should have

1211
01:29:24,780 --> 01:29:27,942
Maybe the meeting should be the following.

1212
01:29:28,903 --> 01:29:34,526
A, that we have a meeting with the city's retirement board.

1213
01:29:35,027 --> 01:29:38,789
Ann Baker, she's our auditor, and I believe she sits on the board anyway.

1214
01:29:39,570 --> 01:29:42,672
What is the total amount of the unfunded liability?

1215
01:29:43,112 --> 01:29:47,154
The unfunded pension liability, how much is that?

1216
01:29:47,174 --> 01:29:47,995
As of which date?

1217
01:29:48,375 --> 01:29:48,895
As of today.

1218
01:29:49,356 --> 01:29:49,936
As of today.

1219
01:29:50,456 --> 01:29:54,399
The unfunded pension liability as of today, number one.

1220
01:29:55,057 --> 01:29:56,158
Point of information, Mr. President.

1221
01:29:56,218 --> 01:29:57,299
Point of information, counsel.

1222
01:29:57,319 --> 01:30:10,207
If the federal government has changed their standards and they're making the municipalities and the states report their unfunded liabilities differently than they have required them to do in the past, then this information and data that we're getting isn't going to be accurate.

1223
01:30:10,708 --> 01:30:18,913
If they're not reporting the liabilities the way that GASB and the way that the generally accepted accounting principles are calling for, then they can give us all the data in the world.

1224
01:30:19,033 --> 01:30:21,335
But if they're not giving us a forecasted

1225
01:30:22,198 --> 01:30:29,423
You know, if they're not giving us a forecasted, estimated liability that's done properly, it's garbage in, garbage out.

1226
01:30:30,164 --> 01:30:32,626
Well, that's Councilor Knight's opinion.

1227
01:30:32,946 --> 01:30:36,768
As of right now, let's just see, what is the unfunded liability?

1228
01:30:36,909 --> 01:30:37,909
How is that determined?

1229
01:30:38,149 --> 01:30:40,731
If you want to use the Gatsby, the new federal, I don't have no idea.

1230
01:30:40,951 --> 01:30:43,713
Let's just see, because they're the ones that have to deal with this on a daily basis.

1231
01:30:44,014 --> 01:30:47,316
The unfunded liability, what's the due date that has to be paid out?

1232
01:30:51,029 --> 01:30:52,090
And Committee of the Whole?

1233
01:30:52,110 --> 01:30:53,310
Committee of the Whole.

1234
01:30:53,490 --> 01:30:53,570
Sure.

1235
01:30:53,590 --> 01:30:54,090
Committee of the Whole.

1236
01:30:55,251 --> 01:30:55,651
All those?

1237
01:30:57,831 --> 01:30:59,532
Councilor Marks, and then Councilor De La Russo.

1238
01:31:00,132 --> 01:31:01,092
Thank you, Mr. President.

1239
01:31:01,393 --> 01:31:05,234
I think the one good thing is we're all in agreement here, behind the reeling, from what I hear.

1240
01:31:05,734 --> 01:31:08,055
And I think it's prudent to have this particular meeting.

1241
01:31:08,435 --> 01:31:11,876
I thank Councilor Penta for starting the ball rolling on this.

1242
01:31:12,256 --> 01:31:18,318
This impacts a lot of people that are in the retirement system, and it really needs to be reviewed by the city.

1243
01:31:19,037 --> 01:31:23,898
And as was mentioned, the longer we wait, the bigger the unfunded liability becomes.

1244
01:31:24,518 --> 01:31:31,500
And at some point, it's going to become something that we're not going to even want to approach because it's so unapproachable to figure.

1245
01:31:31,840 --> 01:31:34,400
So I thank my colleague for bringing this up.

1246
01:31:37,401 --> 01:31:43,522
If we could just amend this to include the Director of Personnel, Budget, and Finance.

1247
01:31:45,263 --> 01:31:45,703
As amended.

1248
01:31:46,758 --> 01:31:48,959
And also further, can we get a separate report?

1249
01:31:49,740 --> 01:31:57,545
What, if any, finances, financial remuneration does the city of Medford get out of the Medicare drug subsidy?

1250
01:32:01,107 --> 01:32:02,869
And the updated actuarials, we should have it.

1251
01:32:02,929 --> 01:32:04,069
Yeah, we can do that.

1252
01:32:05,690 --> 01:32:05,951
Is that it?

1253
01:32:06,171 --> 01:32:06,331
Yep.

1254
01:32:06,651 --> 01:32:06,911
All right.

1255
01:32:07,752 --> 01:32:08,352
On the motion.

1256
01:32:08,933 --> 01:32:09,993
Roll call vote and have that voted.

1257
01:32:10,013 --> 01:32:15,517
Roll call has been requested for a meeting of the committee of the whole to discuss this with the retirement board.

1258
01:32:16,593 --> 01:32:22,896
And Baker as her role as the retirement board member and the city auditor, as well as budget and personnel director, Stephanie Burke.

1259
01:32:25,857 --> 01:32:26,377
Eddie, you have that?

1260
01:32:26,397 --> 01:32:27,517
Because you look like you had a little.

1261
01:32:29,698 --> 01:32:29,898
Yes.

1262
01:32:34,760 --> 01:32:36,381
But we want that information at the committee.

1263
01:32:36,541 --> 01:32:36,701
Right.

1264
01:32:36,821 --> 01:32:38,422
If we can get that information ahead of time so we can discuss it.

1265
01:32:38,442 --> 01:32:40,483
So we have some information to discuss.

